ctions about actually persisting the file, mark it as IN_PROGRESS, and note this recurring failure pattern in Known Issues. Before I finalize, let me double-check that the other files like app.ts are properly set up.\n\nI'm scanning through the implementation and catching a critical issue: app.ts imports NotificationToast from a file that doesn't exist, which will cause a compile error. The other notification components look solid, but that missing file is blocking everything. There's also a subtle design question about how the unread badge counter works—right now it just increments on each notification event, but if users dismiss notifications without opening the panel, the count gets out of sync with reality. disappears when center opened or cleared\". Dismissing individual notifications doesn't reset the badge, which seems like a minor UX issue but not a spec violation.\n\nLooking at the `toggleNotificationCenter` function, it resets the unread count to 0 when the panel opens, but not when it closes—so new notifications after closing will still show up in the badge. That behavior tracks correctly.\n\nThe `notifd.connect(\"notified\", ...)` handler fires for each notification, but there's a potential bootstrap issue: if pending notifications exist when the center first launches, the badge won't display them since that signal hasn't fired yet. It's an edge case the spec doesn't explicitly address.\n\nThe `ClearAllButton` uses a reactive binding to `notifd.notifications`, so it should hide properly when the list empties after dismissing individual items. That part seems solid.\n\nThe critical blocker is still the missing NotificationToast.tsx file. I should also scan the remaining source files to verify there are no lingering `swaync-client` references left in the codebase.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":484,"cache_read_input_tokens":67003,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens"