{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019AMScmcj18ng21v2KpFHAM","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→import app from \"ags/gtk4/app\"\n     2→import style from \"./style.scss\"\n     3→import { BarLeft } from \"./widgets/BarLeft\"\n     4→import { BarCenter } from \"./widgets/BarCenter\"\n     5→import { BarRight } from \"./widgets/BarRight\"\n     6→import { ServicePanel } from \"./widgets/ServiceStatus\"\n     7→import { NotificationCenter } from \"./widgets/NotificationCenter\"\n     8→import { NotificationToast } from \"./widgets/NotificationToast\"\n     9→\n    10→app.start({\n    11→  instanceName: \"chrysaki-bar\",\n    12→  css: style,\n    13→  main() {\n    14→    app.get_monitors().map((monitor) => {\n    15→      BarLeft(monitor)\n    16→      BarCenter(monitor)\n    17→      BarRight(monitor)\n    18→    })\n    19→    // Single-instance panels (not per-monitor)\n    20→    ServicePanel()\n    21→    NotificationCenter()\n    22→    NotificationToast()\n    23→  },\n    24→})\n    25→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9a9debd4-cb30-40a5-a312-2927fca65333","uuid":"831ff68d-6fba-4f22-8f23-4a974ce5638a","timestamp":"2026-03-17T11:32:45.424Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/kiriketsuki/dots/chrysaki-ralph-ags-notification-center-T11/ags/.config/ags/app.ts","content":"import app from \"ags/gtk4/app\"\nimport style from \"./style.scss\"\nimport { BarLeft } from \"./widgets/BarLeft\"\nimport { BarCenter } from \"./widgets/BarCenter\"\nimport { BarRight } from \"./widgets/BarRight\"\nimport { ServicePanel } from \"./widgets/ServiceStatus\"\nimport { NotificationCenter } from \"./widgets/NotificationCenter\"\nimport { NotificationToast } from \"./widgets/NotificationToast\"\n\napp.start({\n  instanceName: \"chrysaki-bar\",\n  css: style,\n  main() {\n    app.get_monitors().map((monitor) => {\n      BarLeft(monitor)\n      BarCenter(monitor)\n      BarRight(monitor)\n    })\n    // Single-instance panels (not per-monitor)\n    ServicePanel()\n    NotificationCenter()\n    NotificationToast()\n  },\n})\n","numLines":25,"startLine":1,"totalLines":25}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CY6ugNMo6jAUdpzfQ45mPz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. The file `NotificationToast.tsx` needs to be written to disk. The spec's Known Issues section has very specific requirements for what this file needs to contain. Let me write it now.\n\nRequirements from the Known Issues section:\n- `import app from \"ags/gtk4/app\"`\n- `import { Astal, Gtk } from \"ags/gtk4\"`\n- `import AstalNotifd from \"gi://AstalNotifd\"`\n- `import GLib from \"gi://GLib\"`\n- `import { notifd } from \"./NotificationCenter\"`\n- Layer-shell window: TOP|RIGHT anchor, marginTop 48, marginRight 8, namespace \"chrysaki-notification-toast\"\n\n\n- MAX_VISIBLE=4 with FIFO queue management, 5-second auto-dismiss timers, and DND-aware filtering that skips toasts when do-not-disturb is active\n- Individual toast rows displaying app name, summary, and body with close buttons, plus critical urgency styling\n- Signal handlers for the notifd \"notified\" and \"resolved\" events to manage the queue\n\nI have enough context from the existing patterns to build this component now. layer-shell window (like NotificationCenter but for toasts)\n2. Have a FIFO queue with MAX_VISIBLE=4\n3. Auto-dismiss after 5000ms\n4. Skip toasts if DND is enabled\n5. Show ToastRow components with app/summary/body labels + close button\n6. Apply `notif-toast-critical` class for CRITICAL urgency\n\nThe key challenge is the approach: how do we create a toast window in AGS? Looking at NotificationCenter, it uses a single window with a list. For toasts, we need a similar approach but with a queue and auto-dismiss timer.\n\nThe approach I'll use:\n- A single layer-shell window that holds a vertical box of toast rows\n- The toast rows are managed via a module-level queue\n- When a notification comes in:\n  - If DND is enabled, skip\n  - Add to the visible list or queue depending on space\n  - Start a 5s timeout to auto-dismiss\n- When dismissed, remove from visible and promote any queued items\n\nFor state management, I need to handle the reactive updates carefully. AGS/GTK4 with JSX makes it tricky without GObject bindings, but I can follow the NotificationCenter pattern of using module-level arrays for visible and queued toasts, then directly update the GTK widget when the state changes rather than relying on reactive bindings. I need to figure out how to handle the reactive bindings in AGS for the toast queue. The NotificationCenter uses a reactive pattern with `notifications.as()`, but for toasts I need to track a separate queue and manage the widgets imperatively by adding and removing children from a box. Let me sketch out the implementation using AGS 2's JSX approach where I can grab a reference to the container and manipulate it directly.\n\nSetting up the toast window and queue management... Building the toast notification layout...\n\nI'm realizing the tricky part is tracking which notification corresponds to which widget so I can remove it from the list when dismissed. I'll need a Map to store that relationship, and I should think through how AGS 2's JSX approach handles conditional rendering when I'm managing this imperatively with a container. Writing the toast management logic... Building the toast notification UI...\n\nActually, I need to verify how AGS 2 handles JSX returns—whether it directly produces GTK widgets or wraps them in some AGS abstraction. Let me check the NotificationCenter component to see how other widgets are structured there.\n\nLooking at the pattern, JSX in AGS 2 is syntactic sugar that calls `new Widget({...})` under the hood, so a `<box>` element should give me a direct reference to the Gtk.Box. For the toast approach, I need to set up the state and capture the box reference before creating the window, then dynamically add and remove toast rows with GLib.timeout_add for auto-dismissal.\n\nSetting up the component structure... Setting up the resolved signal handler to remove dismissed toasts from the queue, then returning the window. I'm double-checking the notification ID signature for the \"notified\" signal in AstalNotifd to make sure I'm handling it correctly. I can use `notifd.get_notification(id)` directly in the notified handler to retrieve the notification details by ID. The existing code ignores the signal arguments, but I need to capture them to get the notification data for the toast. I should also consider how the toast window visibility should be managed when notifications arrive and are cleared.\n\nFor managing the window, I'll use `app.get_window()` to fetch the window reference dynamically rather than storing it at the module level, which keeps things cleaner. I can store the box reference in a module variable that gets set when the component mounts, then use that to manage the toast list and toggle visibility based on whether there are active notifications.\n\nWriting the implementation... Writing notification management logic... Building the toast row widget... Setting up event listeners for the notification daemon to handle new notifications and resolved ones, then wrapping everything in a window positioned at the top-right corner with the appropriate styling and anchoring.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the alignment values — looking at how NotificationCenter uses numeric constants directly for `halign` rather than the enum names, so I should follow that same pattern for consistency. The type casting might also be redundant if AGS JSX already handles the widget types properly.\n\nFor the timeout callback, `GLib.SOURCE_REMOVE` is `false` and `GLib.SOURCE_CONTINUE` is `true`, with `GLib.PRIORITY_DEFAULT` being `0`. The main concern is handling the null case when `notifd.get_notification(id)` doesn't find a notification.\n\nThere's a potential race condition where a notification gets dismissed by the user before the timeout fires—when that happens, `dismissToast(id)` becomes a no-op since the ID won't be in the `visibleIds` array anymore, which is fine. The GTK4 methods like `remove()` and `append()` should work as expected for managing the toast widgets.\n\nI'm also noticing that the signal connections are set up differently between NotificationCenter and NotificationToast—the former connects at module level while the latter connects inside the function. Since NotificationToast is only called once from app.ts, duplicate handlers shouldn't be an issue, but it's worth keeping in mind. I should verify how the Gtk type imports work in AGS 2 to make sure the Box reference is correct. The `notifd` instance from NotificationCenter is reused here to avoid duplicating the singleton, and multiple signal listeners on the same object work fine in GJS. I'm also checking the `halign` numeric values used elsewhere—they map to `Gtk.Align` constants like `START`, `END`, and `CENTER`.\n\nFor the label properties, `xalign={0}` controls text alignment within the label, `wrap` enables text wrapping, and `ellipsize={3}` sets the ellipsize mode to `END`. These match the patterns already in NotificationCenter, so I'll follow the same conventions for consistency.\n\nNow I need to finalize the implementation and make sure the `GLib.timeout_add` callback returns a boolean as expected...\n\nWriting the implementation... I'm realizing the JSX compiler in AGS should already handle the type correctly—`<box />` returns a `Gtk.Box` which extends `Gtk.Widget`, so I don't need extra type assertions. The real constraint is that my `rowWidgets` map stores `Gtk.Widget` instances, and both `remove()` and `append()` methods on the list box accept `Gtk.Widget` parameters, so the types should align without casting. I need to understand how AGS actually handles JSX types—at runtime, `<box />` should return a real `Gtk.Box` widget, but TypeScript's type inference depends on how the framework defines its JSX namespace, so I might not need the cast at all if the types are set up correctly. I'm reconsidering whether the imperative approach of storing widget references is the best way forward. Maybe I should lean into a reactive pattern instead, using a module-level array of notification objects with reactive bindings like AGS uses elsewhere in the codebase, rather than directly manipulating the Gtk.Box.\n\nActually, thinking about this differently—what if each toast is its own separate window that appears and disappears independently? That would sidestep the need for imperative manipulation of a container altogether.\n\nWriting toast window code... I'm realizing the single-window approach with a dynamic child list is cleaner than managing multiple windows. In GTK4, I can use `Gtk.Box.append()` and `Gtk.Box.remove()` to add and remove notification widgets directly, though I'll need to handle TypeScript's type assertions since AGS JSX might not have perfect type inference for the resulting widget instances.\n\nSetting up the implementation with module-level state to track visible and queued notification IDs, maintaining a map of notification widgets, and initializing the list box container... Building the toast notification row...\n\nNow I'm implementing the function that displays a toast notification by retrieving it from the notification daemon, adding it to the visible list, creating the row element, storing it in a map for reference, and appending it to the list box. I'm also setting up a timer to automatically dismiss the notification after a set duration and updating the visibility state.\n\nThen I'm handling the queue logic where if we're below the maximum visible notifications, we show it immediately, otherwise we add it to the queue. I'm also setting up the main notification toast component that creates the container box and connects to the notification daemon's signals to handle new notifications and resolved ones, managing both the visible and queued notification lists. I'm verifying the implementation against the requirements—checking that the notification system properly handles the max visible limit, auto-dismiss timing, do-not-disturb awareness, styling for critical urgency levels, and the signal connections for new and resolved notifications. Now I need to confirm whether `notifd.get_notification(id)` is actually available in the AstalNotifd API. I need to verify the signal callback signatures match what AGS expects—the first parameter should be the Notifd instance itself, followed by the event-specific arguments like the notification ID and reason code. Let me check how NotificationCenter.tsx handles these callbacks to ensure consistency. Setting up the signal handler... I'm realizing the `notified` signal passes the notification ID and a replaced flag directly to the handler, so I can connect with `(_: unknown, id: number) => enqueue(id)` to capture just the ID I need. TypeScript might have specific type definitions for this signal in AGS, so I should check how the `connect` method is typed to make sure my handler signature matches what's expected. I'm realizing that relying on the notifications array is unreliable—if signals fire rapidly in succession, I might grab the wrong notification. The safer approach is to extract the ID directly from the signal callback parameters, which AGS should provide when the \"notified\" event fires.\n\nSetting up signal handlers... I'm overthinking the type system here—let me just write a straightforward implementation that works at runtime and uses reasonable TypeScript types that match the existing codebase patterns. Setting up the notification toast system... Building the toast notification UI...\n\nNow I'm implementing the logic to display toasts—when a notification comes in, I add it to the visible list, create the row component, and set a timer to automatically dismiss it after a few seconds. The enqueue function checks if do-not-disturb is enabled and whether there's room to show more notifications.\n\nSetting up the main notification toast component with event listeners that handle new notifications and resolved ones, managing the queue as toasts appear and disappear.\n\nNow I'm verifying the type imports are consistent with how the notification system uses `AstalNotifd.Notification` throughout the codebase, then I'll write this to disk. I'm verifying the GLib type definitions in the TypeScript bindings—`GLib.SOURCE_REMOVE` is typed as `false` and `GLib.PRIORITY_DEFAULT` is `0`, so those should work fine. Now I'm ready to write out the implementation.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3588,"cache_read_input_tokens":57523,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3588},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9a9debd4-cb30-40a5-a312-2927fca65333","uuid":"4552e6f1-4087-4967-87ea-1acda3813fd1"}
